description: On May 11, in Venezuela, the Patria Survey entered a new phase and was updated to allow the public to vote on quarantine measures to help make the social life of Venezuelans more flexible. The survey will still include a health map of COVID-19.
type_text: The Government has updated a survey that has been activated since March to get public input into lockdown policies.

description: Starting on April 26, the Venezuelan Government will activate a new national survey through the Patria Platform in order to improve the prevention and containment measures of COVID-19.
type_text: The Government has activated a survey to improve the containment measures that have been place in the country since March.

description: On May 14, the Supreme Court of Justice (TSJ) of Venezuela extended the guard system of its personnel for 30 days to guarantee the service of administration of justice in the country in the context of the COVID-19 pandemic.
type_text: The Supreme Court of Justice of Venezuela is passing a guard system for its staff in order to keep judicial procedures moving during the pandemic.

description: On March 22, the Venezuelan government approved the exemption of taxes, fees, and payment of any import duty on raw materials, capital goods, and supplies.

description: From June 1, President Maduro of Venezuela announced the incorporation of 1,300 Yutong buses to strengthen the national public transport system along with the new flexibilization plan. This will serve 26 public transportation routes.

description: On June 1, Venezuela published handwashing and body hygiene techniques, recommending that the public "wash their hands frequently with soap and water using the proper technique, before leaving the house, when arriving at work or destination, before and after eating and using the toilet, before returning to the home and upon arrival, as well as after coughing, sneezing, and touching potentially contaminated surfaces. In the absence of soap and water, solutions or gels with 70% alcohol can be used."

description: On August 3, President Maduro of Venezuela instructed the Presidential Commission for the Prevention, Attention, and Control of COVID-19 to attend to three tasks: implementing effective measures for migrants entering through legal border crossings, enforcing rules of radical quarantine to stop the spread of COVID-19, and taking a greater effort in reversing moderate and serious cases to decrease the death toll.

description: Venezuela announced on March 13th the obligation to use face masks for all passengers using the subway system in the capital of Caracas.
